  <mads:note type="source">Brill's New Pauly:  "From Orchomenus; Plutarch in his &#x2018;Banquet of the Seven Sages has C. 
      taking part in the conversations as a poet (Mor. 156f), contemporary and close friend of  Periander, tyrant of Corinth 
      (end of the 7th/beginning 6th cent. BC). Two hexameters by the poet (Paus. 9,38,9), in which the city's hero Aspledon 
      is described as the son of Poseidon and Midea, are supposed to attest to the accuracy of local tradition in the Boeotian city of the same name...."
